Women and children are the ones that suffer the most from this including: sexual violence, physical beatings, female genital mutilation (FGM), widow’s rights denied and sexual assault. Not only do victims of rape and trafficking often find themselves discriminated against and stigmatised by their own communities but they also find themselves turned away from hospital facilities on the basis that they have become ‘impure’. Particularly concerning is the fact that rape and trafficking is also common during the conflict in South Sudan.

Globally the fight for women’s rights and the right to speak freely has become increasingly contested. From Gender discrimination regarding the right of Muslim women to be educated and participate in the political sphere to the ban on abortion for the nearly 60 million women without access to safe and legal services in poor and middle-income countries, women’s rights face greater challenges now than ever before. In particular the past 12 months have seen an increase in the re-criminalzisation of abortion, in the North of Ireland, in Northern Virginia and in Uruguay and Chile. Last year Brazilian politicians and some of the majority of their citizens voted against an earlier bill for abortion that would allow it in life-threatening situations, rape or foetal abnormality. Last year the Jamaican government criminalised some aspects of reproductive health services.
